P2 lunar-service reproducibility fixtures
=========================================

These CSVs are REPRODUCIBILITY drift-guard goldens, NOT independent-truth
references. They are consumed by:
  - tests/validate_p2_nsweep_table.rs           (nsweep_golden.csv)
  - tests/validate_p2_spatial_map.rs            (spatial_map_golden.csv)
  - tests/validate_p2_beacon_before_after_golden.csv (beacon_before_after_golden.csv)

They are not part of the Kshana source and are not shipped in the published
crates/packages — they exist only for the test suite.

Why there is no independent oracle
----------------------------------
Each file is an AGGREGATE (order statistics / availability fractions / a
before-after DOP table) of an ILLUSTRATIVE, public-source ELFO constellation.
The aggregate is a property of a CHOSEN geometry, not a physically-fixed
quantity, so no external tool can supply "the" correct value for it. What CAN be
externally validated — and already is, elsewhere in this suite — is the
machinery underneath:
  - the per-sample DOP kernel (orbit::dop) vs gnss_lib_py 1.0.4
    (tests/dop_reference.rs, tests/fixtures/dop/);
  - the per-cell satellite visibility (5 deg mask + limb) vs ANISE 0.10.2
    (tests/lunar_navigation_service_volume_reference.rs);
  - the beacon-visibility horizon vs the L01 airless closed form
    (src/lunar_beacon.rs unit tests).
These fixtures therefore pin only the DETERMINISTIC REPRODUCIBILITY of the
aggregation pipeline (sweep_over_n / coverage / dop_with_beacons) on a fixed
scenario — a drift guard.

Relationship to the paper's headline numbers
---------------------------------------------
The paper P2 quotes specific magnitudes (median GDOP 16.2 -> 1.6 for the -80 deg
user, 24-sat comparison 3.4) that are produced by the kshana-pro PACKAGING
HARNESS with a specific ELFO element set and beacon placement that are NOT part
of this public repo. The public engine, run on the fully-specified public
scenario recorded in these fixtures, produces its OWN before/after table (6-sat
GDOP ~11.7 -> ~5.0 with three beacons; 24-sat median ~2.9). The tests reproduce
THOSE public values exactly, and assert the qualitative MECHANISM the paper's
magnitudes illustrate (beacons collapse the polar GDOP; expanding the
constellation is an alternative route below the usable threshold). They do NOT
assert the literal 16.2/1.6/3.4 numbers, because the public code does not emit
them; claiming otherwise would be dishonest.

Provenance / reproducibility
----------------------------
Generated by the committed examples/gen_p2_lunar_service_fixtures.rs, which is
the single source of truth for the scenario definitions (grid, horizon, mask,
threshold, beacon sites, satellite count). Regenerate with:
  cargo run --example gen_p2_lunar_service_fixtures
The scenario definitions are duplicated verbatim in each validate_p2_*.rs test,
so the tests are self-contained and do not require Python or the generator at
runtime. All values are stored to 17 significant decimal digits ({:.17e}),
which round-trips to the identical f64, so regeneration is bit-exact for the
deterministic engine.

Scenario (shared)
-----------------
Constellation:  LunarConstellation::illustrative_lcns(N)
                (sma = R_moon + 8000 km, e = 0.6, i = 57.7 deg, argp = 90 deg,
                 raan & mean anomaly phased 360*k/N).
Grid:           latitudes {-90, -80, -70} deg x longitudes {-120, 0, 120} deg.
Horizon:        12 h at 1 h steps (13 epochs, t = 0..43200 s).
Elevation mask: 5 deg.  PDOP/GDOP usable threshold: 6.
Beacons:        three surveyed surface sites at (-80,0), (-79,60), (-79,-60) deg
                on 2 km masts; user at (-80, 0) deg on a 2 m mast.

Formats
-------
nsweep_golden.csv:              n_sats,coverage_fraction,gdop_median,frac_below_gdop6
spatial_map_golden.csv:         lat_deg,lon_deg,gdop_median,coverage_fraction,
                                frac_below_gdop6,mean_visible,min_sats,max_sats
beacon_before_after_golden.csv: label,gdop,pdop,hdop,vdop,tdop
An empty numeric field denotes None (no defined DOP / fewer than four sources).
